SIMPLE: snare
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snare
<hw>Snare</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>snear</ets>a
cord, a string; akin to D. <ets>snoer</ets>, G. <ets>schnur</ets>, OHG.
<ets>snour</ets> a cord, <ets>snarahha</ets> a noose, Dan.
<ets>snare</ets>, Sw. & Icel. <ets>snara</ets>, Goth.
<ets>sn<?/rj<?/</ets> a basket; and probably also to E.
<ets>needle</ets>. See <er>Needle</er>, and cf. <er>Snarl</er> to
entangle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A contrivance, often consisting of a
noose of cord, or the like, by which a bird or other animal may be
entangled and caught; a trap; a gin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, anything by which one is entangled and
brought into trouble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If thou retire, the Dauphin, well appointed,⟦br⟧
Stands with the <qex>snares</qex> of war to tangle thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The gut or string stretched across the lower head of
a drum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An instrument, consisting usually
of a wireloop or noose, for removing tumors, etc., by
avulsion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Snare drum</b></col>, <cd>the smaller common military
drum, as distinguished from the <xex>bass drum</xex>; -- so called
because (in order to render it more resonant) it has stretched across
its lower head a catgut string or strings.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snare</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Snare
<hw>Snare</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Snared</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Snaring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To catch with a snare; to
insnare; to entangle; hence, to bring into unexpected evil, perplexity,
or danger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lest that too heavenly form . . . <qex>snare</qex> them.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mournful crocodile⟦br⟧
With sorrow <qex>snares</qex> relenting passengers.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snarer</ent>⟦br⟧
